<typeStatus id="8B4F8836FFE15074FF4E6180FF19E891" box="[136,197,195,221]" pageId="38" pageNumber="156">typus</typeStatus>
collection. It was described by 
<bibRefCitation id="30654B65FFE15074FDF56181FC95E890" author="Irwin, H. S. &amp; Barneby, R. C." box="[563,841,194,220]" pageId="38" pageNumber="156" pagination="1 - 277" refId="ref22204" refString="Irwin, H. S. &amp; Barneby, R. C. (1978) Monographic studies in Cassia (Leguminosae-Caesalpinioideae) III. Sections Absus and Grimaldia. Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden 30: 1 - 277. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 2806200" type="journal article" year="1978">Irwin &amp; Barneby (1978)</bibRefCitation>
who cited that its could be an intermediate specimen (hybrid) between some taxa belonging to the series 
<taxonomicName id="93F44D17FFE15074FD1861A4FCE8E94D" authority="Irwin &amp; Barneby, 1978" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Barneby" authorityYear="1982" baseAuthorityName="Irwin &amp; Barneby" baseAuthorityYear="1972" box="[734,820,231,257]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Absus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="38" pageNumber="156" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="series" series="Setosae">
<emphasis id="6680EA86FFE15074FD1861A4FCE8E94D" box="[734,820,231,257]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="156">Setosae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="93F44D17FFE15074FCA961A4FC15E94C" authority="Irwin &amp; Barneby, 1978" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Barneby" authorityYear="1982" baseAuthorityName="Irwin &amp; Barneby" baseAuthorityYear="1978" box="[879,969,231,256]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Absus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="38" pageNumber="156" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="series" series="Ursinae">
<emphasis id="6680EA86FFE15074FCA961A4FC15E94C" box="[879,969,231,256]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="156">Ursinae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. After its description, 
<taxonomicName id="93F44D17FFE15074FB0B61A5FAABE94C" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Barneby" authorityYear="1982" baseAuthorityName="H. S. Irwin &amp; Barneby" box="[1229,1399,230,256]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Chamaecrista" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="38" pageNumber="156" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amphibola">
<emphasis id="6680EA86FFE15074FB0B61A5FAABE94C" box="[1229,1399,230,256]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="156">Ch. amphibola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was never collected again and analyzing the morphology of its 
<typeStatus id="8B4F8836FFE15074FCED6048FCB4E969" box="[811,872,267,293]" pageId="38" pageNumber="156">typus</typeStatus>
collection, we concluded that it is more similar to 
<taxonomicName id="93F44D17FFE15074FF4E606DFEC2E904" box="[136,286,302,328]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Cassia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="38" pageNumber="156" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="exsudans">
<emphasis id="6680EA86FFE15074FF4E606DFEC2E904" box="[136,286,302,328]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="156">Ch. exsudans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the series 
<taxonomicName id="93F44D17FFE15074FE12606CFDF2E904" authority="Irwin &amp; Barneby, 1978" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Barneby" authorityYear="1982" baseAuthorityName="Irwin &amp; Barneby" baseAuthorityYear="1978" box="[468,558,303,328]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Absus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="38" pageNumber="156" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="series" series="Ursinae">
<emphasis id="6680EA86FFE15074FE12606CFDF2E904" box="[468,558,303,328]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="156">Ursinae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than other species of 
<emphasis id="6680EA86FFE15074FCE3606CFCA7E905" box="[805,891,303,329]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="156">Setosae</emphasis>
, mainly for having 3 or more pairs of leaflets and abundant stellate trichomes in vegetative and reproductive parts, which led us to consider 
<taxonomicName id="93F44D17FFE15074FBAC6011FAD3E920" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Barneby" authorityYear="1982" baseAuthorityName="H. S. Irwin &amp; Barneby" box="[1130,1295,338,364]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Chamaecrista" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="38" pageNumber="156" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amphibola">
<emphasis id="6680EA86FFE15074FBAC6011FAD3E920" box="[1130,1295,338,364]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="156">Ch. amphibola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a synonym for 
<taxonomicName id="93F44D17FFE15074FF746035FE95E9DC" box="[178,329,374,400]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Cassia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="38" pageNumber="156" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="exsudans">
<emphasis id="6680EA86FFE15074FF746035FE95E9DC" box="[178,329,374,400]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="156">Ch. exsudans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Considering that both species were described in the same work, and that 
<taxonomicName id="93F44D17FFE15074FB666035FAE4E9DC" box="[1184,1336,374,400]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Cassia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="38" pageNumber="156" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="exsudans">
<emphasis id="6680EA86FFE15074FB666035FAE4E9DC" box="[1184,1336,374,400]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="156">Ch. exsudans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a more collected and known taxon than 
<taxonomicName id="93F44D17FFE15074FE3560D8FD50E9F8" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Barneby" authorityYear="1982" baseAuthorityName="H. S. Irwin &amp; Barneby" box="[499,652,410,437]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Chamaecrista" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="38" pageNumber="156" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amphibola">
<emphasis id="6680EA86FFE15074FE3560D8FD50E9F8" box="[499,652,410,437]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="156">C. amphibola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, we opted for the binomial as valid.
</paragraph>
